B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: Develops, demonstrates, and transitions directed energy modeling simulation and analysis to support both radio-
frequency and laser bioeffects advanced demonstrations. Develop and demonstrate modeling capabilities to assess collateral
hazards from high power directed energy systems, including the use of probabilistic risk assessment techniques and analysis
of system-level effects on warfighters. Additionally, develop and demonstrate counter directed energy weapons technologies for
aircrew and ground personnel to provide protection against directed energy threats. The project integrates bioeffects and human
performance models from across the Department of the Air Force (DAF) in support of Digital Transformation initiatives.

FY 2026 Plans:
-Continue to provide hazard analysis for directed energy and novel weapon systems under development, demonstrating new
validated capabilities for personnel hazard assessments by conducting reflectance measurements and analysis to support the
required directed energy weapon review and approval process.
-Continue to provide human-based design requirements optimizing operational and mission performance for counter-directed
energy weapon technologies by providing subject matter expertise and modeling & simulation analysis.
-Continue to demonstrate and integrate high peak power radio frequency and laser human effects assessment models and tools
to address real world concerns by providing modeling and simulation analysis as well as subject matter expertise for laser and
radio frequency safety standards
-Continue the integration of radio frequency and optical radiation hazards and behavioral analysis into engagement-level
modeling, simulation and analysis tools for future transitions in mission-level tool suites to support formal studies and analyses.
-Continue development of integrated vision modeling libraries to optimize agile laser eye protection technologies including
integrating modeling and simulation capabilities into existing architectures for weaponeering and mission level analyses.
-Continue development of the Agile Laser Eye Protection Analysis Tool to produce an integrated modeling environment for
optimizing devices for optical radiation eye protection, and to mitigate the visual impact of optical radiation on airman-machine
interfaces, visual performance, and operational effectiveness.
-Continue the environment validation phase of operational reference mission analysis of directed energy collateral effects at
advanced technology class of targets, enabling mid-term employment of directed energy weapons by delivering an updated
probabilistic/deterministic laser risk assessment tool for airborne laser target designators.
-Complete the Virtual Reality component for vision effects through transition of laser dazzle simulations into operational
applications including development and testing of plug-ins of Bioeffects models and integrating them into wargaming and
simulation laboratories.
FY 2027 Plans:
-Continue providing hazard analysis for directed energy and novel weapon systems, maturing modeling capabilities to improve
hazard assessments and conducting performance analysis to support the required directed energy weapon review and approval
process for novel systems.

